MSH|^~\&|LabMaster|nutrpath|||20260513072228+1000||ORU^R01^ORU_R01|202605130722271AF966|P|2.3.1^AUS&Australia&ISO3166-1|||ER|AL|AUSPID|1||P000065^^^NutriPATH^PI||PATIENT^Test^^^Ms||19700101|F|||123 Home Avenue^^Test Suburb^VIC^3125^AUPV1|1|O||||||^BioTek^*^^^^^^AUSHICPR|^BioTek^*^^^^^^AUSHICPROBR|1||26096-0001^nutrpath^0001^GUID|^^0001||20260402000000+1000|20260406000000+1000|||||||20260406000000+1000|URINE, SPOT&URINE, SPOT&0001|^BioTek^*^^^^^^AUSHICPR||||||20260513072228+1000|||F||^^^20260402000000OBX|1|FT|ORGANIC_ACIDS_INTROD^ORGANIC ACIDS INTRODUCTION^0001|1|The Organic Acids Test (OAT) is a comprehensive urine-based analysis that examines over 120 individual metabolic markers across the following key domains: Microbial Overgrowth - Identifies markers associated with bacterial dysbiosis and overgrowth of potentially pathogenic organisms in the gastrointestinal tract, including phenolic and aromatic compounds produced by microbial fermentation of dietary substrates.||||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|2|FT|ORGANIC_ACIDS_INTROD^ORGANIC ACIDS INTRODUCTION^0001|2|Please Note:  We acknowledge that certain compounds appear in multiple sections of the report. This is intentional, as these analytes have relevance across different clinical pathways. Their inclusion in multiple categories supports more accurate pattern recognition and enhances the interpretive value of Organic Acids testing.||||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|3|FT|ORGANIC_ACIDS_INTROD^ORGANIC ACIDS INTRODUCTION^0001|3|Organic acids are small carbon-based molecules produced as by-products of everyday metabolic processes in the body. They are measurable in urine and serve as functional windows into the biochemical pathways that govern energy production, detoxification, immune regulation, neurotransmitter synthesis, and nutritional status. Organic acid testing offers a uniquely deep and clinically meaningful picture of a patient's metabolic health.||||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|4|FT|ORGANIC_ACIDS_INTROD^ORGANIC ACIDS INTRODUCTION^0001|4|Yeast &amp; Fungal Metabolites - Screens for metabolites associated with yeast and fungal overgrowth, including Candida-related markers such as arabinitol, tartaric acid, and tricarballylic acid, which may interfere with mitochondrial function and nutrient absorption.||||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|5|FT|ORGANIC_ACIDS_INTROD^ORGANIC ACIDS INTRODUCTION^0001|5|Mitochondrial &amp; Energy Metabolism - Evaluates the functional integrity of the citric acid (TCA) cycle through measurement of key intermediates including citric acid, cis-aconitic acid, isocitric acid, and alpha-ketoglutaric acid.||||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|6|FT|ORGANIC_ACIDS_INTROD^ORGANIC ACIDS INTRODUCTION^0001|6|Fatty Acid Oxidation &amp; Ketone Metabolism - Assesses the efficiency of both mitochondrial beta-oxidation and the alternative omega-oxidation pathway through dicarboxylic acid markers, providing insight into fatty acid handling, carnitine sufficiency, and metabolic flexibility.||||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|7|FT|ORGANIC_ACIDS_INTROD^ORGANIC ACIDS INTRODUCTION^0001|7|Amino Acid &amp; Branched-Chain Metabolism - Examines the catabolism of essential and branched-chain amino acids, identifying impairments in leucine, isoleucine, valine, methionine, threonine, and tyrosine pathways that may contribute to fatigue, mood dysregulation, and neurological symptoms.||||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|8|FT|ORGANIC_ACIDS_INTROD^ORGANIC ACIDS INTRODUCTION^0001|8|Neurotransmitter Metabolism -Profiles the major catecholamine and indole pathways, including dopamine, norepinephrine, and serotonin metabolites, as well as the tryptophan-kynurenine pathway, offering functional insight into mood, cognition, stress response, and sleep regulation.||||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|9|FT|ORGANIC_ACIDS_INTROD^ORGANIC ACIDS INTRODUCTION^0001|9|Vitamins &amp; Nutritional Cofactor Markers - Provides functional assessment of B-vitamin status (B1, B2, B3, B5, B6, B12, folate, biotin), glutathione and antioxidant capacity, and key cofactors required for enzymatic activity across multiple metabolic pathways.||||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|10|FT|ORGANIC_ACIDS_INTROD^ORGANIC ACIDS INTRODUCTION^0001|10|Detoxification &amp; Glutathione Function - Evaluates markers of phase I and phase II hepatic detoxification, glutathione cycling via pyroglutamic acid, and NAC status, reflecting the body's capacity to manage oxidative burden and chemical exposure.||||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|11|FT|ORGANIC_ACIDS_INTROD^ORGANIC ACIDS INTRODUCTION^0001|11|Oxidative Stress &amp; Inflammation - Measures markers of DNA oxidative damage and inflammatory mediators, including 8-hydroxy-deoxyguanosine and leukotriene E4, providing a functional picture of systemic oxidative load.||||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|12|FT|ORGANIC_ACIDS_INTROD^ORGANIC ACIDS INTRODUCTION^0001|12|Oxalate Metabolism - Screens for markers of excess oxalate production or absorption, which may be associated with gut dysbiosis, dietary factors, or impaired detoxification.||||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|13|FT|ORGANIC_ACIDS_INTROD^ORGANIC ACIDS INTRODUCTION^0001|13|Environmental &amp; Xenobiotic Exposures - Identifies urinary metabolites of common environmental chemicals including xylene, benzene, toluene, phthalates, parabens, and endocrine-disrupting compounds such as Bisphenol A (BPA) and Bisphenol S (BPS), providing objective evidence of toxic load.||||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|14|NM|BENZOIC_ACID_URINE_S^Benzoic Acid (Urine, Spot)^0001||25.00|mmol/molCR|<9.30|H|||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|15|NM|HIPPURIC_ACID_URINE_^Hippuric Acid (Urine, Spot)^0001||330.0|mmol/molCR|<603.0||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|16|NM|4_HYDROXYBENZOIC_ACI^4-Hydroxybenzoic Acid (4-HBA) (Urine, Spot)^0001||0.64|mmol/molCR|<0.57|H|||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|17|NM|3_4_DIHYDROXYBENZOIC^3,4-Dihydroxybenzoic Acid (3,4-DHBA)^0001||62.00|mmol/molCR|<45.00|H|||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|18|NM|3_HYDROXYPHENYLACETI^3-Hydroxyphenylacetic Acid (3-HPAA)^0001||12.00|mmol/molCR|<10.00|H|||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|19|NM|3_4_DIHYDROXYPHENYLP^3,4-Dihydroxyphenylpropionic Acid (DHPPA)^0001||2.90|mmol/molCR|<5.30||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|20|NM|FURANCARBONYLGLYCINE^Furancarbonylglycine^0001||2.90|mmol/molCR|<2.00|H|||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|21|NM|PHENYLACETIC_ACID_PA^Phenylacetic Acid (PAA)^0001||2.50|mmol/molCR|<3.90||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|22|NM|PHENYLPROPIONIC_ACID^Phenylpropionic Acid^0001||0.08|mmol/molCR|<0.10||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|23|NM|3_PHENYLLACTIC_ACID_^3-Phenyllactic Acid (3-PLA)^0001||1.50|mmol/molCR|<2.00||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|24|NM|2_HYDROXYPHENYLACETI^2-Hydroxyphenylacetic Acid (2-HPAA)^0001||0.60|mmol/molCR|0.05-0.70||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|25|NM|4_HYDROXYPHENYLLACTI^4-Hydroxyphenyllactic Acid (4-HPLA) (Urine, Spot)^0001||3.50|mmol/molCR|<3.90||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|26|NM|3_HYDROXYPROPIONIC_A^3-Hydroxypropionic Acid (3-HPA)^0001||6.60|mmol/molCR|<17.00||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|27|NM|4_CRESOL^4-Cresol^0001||0.90|ug/mgCR|<3.00||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|28|NM|4_HYDROXYPHENYLACETI^4-Hydroxyphenylacetic Acid (4-HPAA)^0001||10.20|mmol/molCR|<14.60||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|29|NM|INDOLEACETIC_ACID_IA^Indoleacetic Acid (IAA)^0001||8.70|mmol/molCR|<11.00||||F|||2026