M_D_GLUCARATE^Calcium-D-glucarate^0001||0.0|mg|||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|184|NM|COENZYME_Q10_URINE_S^Coenzyme Q10 (Urine, Spot)^0001||0.0|mg|||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|185|NM|GLUTATHIONE^Glutathione^0001||0.0|mg|||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|186|NM|N_ACETYLCYSTEINE^N-Acetylcysteine^0001||0.0|mg|||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|187|NM|5_HTP^5-HTP^0001||80.0|mg|||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|188|NM|ACETYL_L_CARNITINE^Acetyl-L-Carnitine^0001||0.0|mg|||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|189|NM|L_ARGININE^L-Arginine^0001||0.0|mg|||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|190|NM|ASPARTIC_ACID^Aspartic Acid^0001||0.0|mg|||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|191|NM|GLUTAMINE^Glutamine^0001||0.0|mg|||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|192|NM|GLYCINE^Glycine^0001||0.0|mg|||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|193|NM|LYSINE^Lysine^0001||0.0|mg|||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|194|NM|METHIONINE^Methionine^0001||0.0|mg|||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|195|NM|ORNITHINE^Ornithine^0001||0.0|mg|||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|196|NM|PHENYLALANINE^Phenylalanine^0001||0.0|mg|||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|197|NM|SERINE^Serine^0001||0.0|mg|||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|198|NM|TAURINE^Taurine^0001||0.0|mg|||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|199|NM|TRYPTOPHAN^Tryptophan^0001||0.0|mg|||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|200|NM|TYROSINE^Tyrosine^0001||0.0|mg|||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|201|NM|D_LACTATE_FREE_PROBI^D-Lactate-free probiotics^0001||20.0|billion CFU|||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|202|NM|LACTOBACILLUS^Lactobacillus^0001||40.0|billion CFU|||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|203|NM|PROBIOTICS_MULTISTRA^Probiotics (Multistrain)^0001||20.0|billion CFU|||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|204|NM|MALIC_ACID^Malic Acid^0001||0.0|mg|||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|205|NM|EPA_DHA^EPA/DHA^0001||0.0|mg|||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|206|NM|FOLINIC_ACID^Folinic Acid^0001||0.0|ug|||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|207|FT|COMMENT^Comment^0001|1|About the Nutrition Guide &amp; Supplement Schedule||||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|208|FT|COMMENT^Comment^0001|2|The Nutrition Guide presented in this report represents a personalised supplementation schedule generated directly from the organic acid findings of this individual patient. It is not a generic recommendation it is dynamically calculated for each patient based on the specific metabolic pattern identified across all measured domains.||||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|209|FT|COMMENT^Comment^0001|3|The schedule is generated using a proprietary weighted algorithm developed by our clinical and scientific team. The algorithm analyses the full pattern of organic acid results not individual markers in isolation and assigns a weighted score to each finding based on its functional significance, its relationship to nutrient-dependent enzymatic pathways, and its interaction with other metabolic markers present in the same report. The outcome of this calculation determines both the nutritional priority level (Adequate, Mild, Moderate, or High) and the suggested starting dose for each nutrient, amino acid, probiotic, or cofactor listed.||||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|210|FT|COMMENT^Comment^0001|4|Important Disclaimer||||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|211|FT|COMMENT^Comment^0001|5|The Nutrition Guide and supplementation suggestions in this report are generated for clinical decision-support purposes only and are not intended as standalone medical advice or a prescription.||||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|212|FT|COMMENT^Comment^0001|6|The proprietary algorithm used to generate this schedule is based on established relationships between organic acid biomarkers and nutritional cofactor requirements. However, it operates solely on biochemical data and cannot account for a patient's complete medical history, current medications, existing diagnoses, organ function, pregnancy or breastfeeding status, or any other health condition that may influence the safety or appropriateness of the suggested nutrients and doses.||||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|213|FT|COMMENT^Comment^0001|7|The final therapeutic decision including whether to implement, modify, or withhold any recommendation in this report rests entirely with the treating practitioner. It is the practitioner's responsibility to integrate these findings with the full clinical picture before making any therapeutic recommendation.||||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|214|FT|COMMENT^Comment^0001|8|This report does not diagnose, treat, cure, or prevent any disease or medical condition.||||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|215|FT|BACTERIAL_DYSBIOSIS_^Bacterial Dysbiosis Comment^0001|1|FURANCARBONYLGLYCINE ELEVATED: Furancarbonylglycine (FCG) is a glycine-conjugated metabolite formed during the hepatic detoxification of furan-derived compounds, which are commonly generated during the thermal processing of foods and from certain environmental exposures.||||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|216|FT|BACTERIAL_DYSBIOSIS_^Bacterial Dysbiosis Comment^0001|2|BENZOIC ACID ELEVATED (URINE): Elevated urinary benzoic acid suggests increased exposure to benzoate-containing foods, preservatives, or altered gut microbial metabolism. Benzoic acid is detoxified primarily through glycine conjugation to form hippuric acid.||||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|217|FT|BACTERIAL_DYSBIOSIS_^Bacterial Dysbiosis Comment^0001|3|Consider: treatment for dysbiosis and diet changes, mucosal support, pre and probiotics||||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|218|FT|BACTERIAL_DYSBIOSIS_^Bacterial Dysbiosis Comment^0001|4|4-HYDROXYBENZOIC ACID ELEVATED (URINE): Elevated urinary 4-hydroxybenzoic acid suggests increased exposure to parabens or altered metabolism of aromatic compounds. It may also arise from gut microbial metabolism of dietary polyphenols.||||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|219|FT|BACTERIAL_DYSBIOSIS_^Bacterial Dysbiosis Comment^0001|5|Consider: Treatment for dysbiosis and diet changes, mucosal support, pre and probiotics.||||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|220|FT|BACTERIAL_DYSBIOSIS_^Bacterial Dysbiosis Comment^0001|6|Suggested Treatment Considerations: Consider review of dietary intake, particularly consumption of highly processed or heat-treated foods. Assessment of environmental exposures may be appropriate where clinically indicated. No specific medical intervention is typically required beyond addressing identifiable sources. Interpretation should be guided by the overall clinical context and associated findings.||||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|221|FT|BACTERIAL_DYSBIOSIS_^Bacterial Dysbiosis Comment^0001|7|3,4-DIHYDROXYBENZOIC ACID ELEVATED: Description: Elevated 3,4-dihydroxybenzoic acid reflects increased catecholamine metabolism, enhanced polyphenol biotransformation by gut microbiota, or oxidative degradation of dopamine.||||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|222|FT|BACTERIAL_DYSBIOSIS_^Bacterial Dysbiosis Comment^0001|8|Clinical Significance: Persistent elevation may indicate excessive catecholamine turnover, increased oxidative stress, or heightened gut microbial phenolic metabolism. Associated with inflammatory states and dysbiosis patterns.||||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|223|FT|BACTERIAL_DYSBIOSIS_^Bacterial Dysbiosis Comment^0001|9|Suggested Treatment: Evaluate catecholamine pathway function and oxidative stress markers. Support antioxidant status with N-acetylcysteine, glutathione precursors, and vitamin C. Address gut dysbiosis if implicated.||||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|224|FT|BACTERIAL_DYSBIOSIS_^Bacterial Dysbiosis Comment^0001|10|3-HYDROXYPHENYLACETIC ACID ELEVATED: Description: Elevated 3-hydroxyphenylacetic acid reflects overgrowth of Clostridia or other aromatic amino acid-fermenting bacteria, producing excessive phenolic metabolites in the gut lumen.||||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|225|FT|BACTERIAL_DYSBIOSIS_^Bacterial Dysbiosis Comment^0001|11|Clinical Significance: Marked elevation is a recognised biomarker of intestinal bacterial overgrowth (particularly Clostridial dysbiosis) and increased gut permeability. Associated with neurological symptoms, fatigue, and cognitive impairment due to systemic absorption of phenolic compounds.||||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|226|FT|BACTERIAL_DYSBIOSIS_^Bacterial Dysbiosis Comment^0001|12|Suggested Treatment: Consider targeted antimicrobial or herbal antimicrobial therapy (e.g., oregano oil, berberine). Implement gut restoration protocol including dietary modification, probiotics, and intestinal barrier support (L-glutamine, zinc carnosine). Retest after intervention.||||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|227|FT|BACTERIAL_DYSBIOSIS_^Bacterial Dysbiosis Comment^0001|13|Clinically, elevated benzoic acid may be associated with headaches, fatigue, gastrointestinal discomfort, or chemical sensitivity, although symptoms are often non-specific.||||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|228|FT|BACTERIAL_DYSBIOSIS_^Bacterial Dysbiosis Comment^0001|14|From an organic acid pattern perspective, elevated benzoic acid may be observed alongside elevated hippuric acid, indicating increased benzoate load or increased demand on glycine-dependent conjugation pathways.||||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|229|FT|BACTERIAL_DYSBIOSIS_^Bacterial Dysbiosis Comment^0001|15|From a functional medicine perspective, elevated benzoic acid should be interpreted in the context of dietary intake, glycine availability, gut microbial activity, and overall detoxification capacity rather than as an isolated finding.||||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|230|FT|BACTERIAL_DYSBIOSIS_^Bacterial Dysbiosis Comment^0001|16|Clinically, elevated levels may be associated with non-specific symptoms such as headaches, fatigue, or chemical sensitivity.||||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|231|FT|BACTERIAL_DYSBIOSIS_^Bacterial Dysbiosis Comment^0001|17|From an organic acid pattern perspective, elevated 4-hydroxybenzoic acid may be observed alongside other aromatic metabolites, reflecting increased aromatic compound load or altered gut microbial activity.||||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|232|FT|BACTERIAL_DYSBIOSIS_^Bacterial Dysbiosis Comment^0001|18|From a functional medicine perspective, this finding should be interpreted in the context of environmental exposure, dietary polyphenol intake, and gut microbiome balance.||||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|233|FT|BACTERIAL_DYSBIOSIS_^Bacterial Dysbiosis Comment^0001|19|Elevated urinary furancarbonylglycine may reflect increased exposure to furan-containing compounds, with subsequent metabolism via glycine conjugation pathways and renal excretion. This is most commonly associated with dietary intake of heat-processed foods, although environmental sources may also contribute.||||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|234|FT|BACTERIAL_DYSBIOSIS_^Bacterial Dysbiosis Comment^0001|20|As a phase II detoxification product, this marker primarily reflects exposure and metabolic processing rather than intrinsic metabolic dysfunction, and is therefore non-specific when interpreted in isolation.||||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|235|FT|YEAST_DYSBIOSIS_COMM^Yeast Dysbiosis Comment^0001|1|ARABINOSE ELEVATED: Arabinose is a pentose sugar that may be detected in urine as a product of dietary intake and gastrointestinal microbial metabolism. It is not a primary endogenous human metabolite and is typically present at low concentrations.||||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|236|FT|YEAST_DYSBIOSIS_COMM^Yeast Dysbiosis Comment^0001|2|Suggested Treatment Considerations: Consider correlation with other markers of gastrointestinal microbial activity and clinical features suggestive of altered gut function. Review dietary intake and factors that may influence microbial balance. Further evaluation of gastrointestinal health may be appropriate where clinically indicated. Management should be guided by the overall clinical context and associated laboratory findings rather than the isolated elevation of this marker.||||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|237|FT|YEAST_DYSBIOSIS_COMM^Yeast Dysbiosis Comment^0001|3|5-HYDROXYMETHYL-2-FUROIC ACID ELEVATED: 5-Hydroxymethyl-2-furoic acid (5-HMFA) is a urinary metabolite derived from the metabolism of 5-hydroxymethylfurfural (HMF), a compound formed during the thermal processing of carbohydrate-containing foods, particularly under high heat conditions (e.g. baking, roasting, or caramelisation).||||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|238|FT|YEAST_DYSBIOSIS_COMM^Yeast Dysbiosis Comment^0001|4|Suggested Treatment Considerations: Review dietary intake, particularly consumption of highly processed or heat-treated foods. Where appropriate, consider reducing intake of foods subjected to high-temperature processing. No specific medical intervention is typically required beyond addressing identifiable dietary sources. Interpretation should be guided by the overall clinical context and associated findings.||||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|239|FT|YEAST_DYSBIOSIS_COMM^Yeast Dysbiosis Comment^0001|5|Elevated urinary arabinose may be associated with increased gastrointestinal microbial production of arabinose, which has been described in the context of altered gut microbial activity, including possible overrepresentation of certain yeast or bacterial species. However, this finding is non-specific and may also be influenced by dietary sources and intestinal metabolism.||||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|240|FT|YEAST_DYSBIOSIS_COMM^Yeast Dysbiosis Comment^0001|6|As such, arabinose should not be used in isolation as a diagnostic marker of a specific organism, and is best interpreted alongside other markers of microbial metabolism and gastrointestinal function.||||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|241|FT|YEAST_DYSBIOSIS_COMM^Yeast Dysbiosis Comment^0001|7|Elevated urinary 5-HMFA typically reflects increased dietary exposure to heat-processed foods, with subsequent hepatic metabolism and excretion. As such, this marker is primarily considered an indicator of dietary intake and exposure, rather than endogenous metabolic dysfunction.||||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|242|FT|YEAST_DYSBIOSIS_COMM^Yeast Dysbiosis Comment^0001|8|In some contexts, elevated levels may also reflect increased formation of furan-derived compounds associated with carbohydrate degradation during cooking. This finding is non-specific and should be interpreted in conjunction with dietary history and other relevant exposure markers.||||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|243|FT|MITOCHONDRIAL_ENERGY^Mitochondrial/Energy Metabolism Comment^0001|1|MEVALONOLACTONE ELEVATED: Mevalonolactone is the lactone form of mevalonic acid, an intermediate in the mevalonate pathway, which is essential for the synthesis of cholesterol, isoprenoids, and other biologically important molecules. This pathway is regulated by HMG-CoA reductase, the rate-limiting enzyme in cholesterol biosynthesis.||||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|244|FT|MITOCHONDRIAL_ENERGY^Mitochondrial/Energy Metabolism Comment^0001|2|ISOCITRIC ACID ELEVATED (URINE): Elevated urinary isocitric acid suggests altered downstream TCA cycle efficiency or compensatory metabolic flux.||||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|245|FT|MITOCHONDRIAL_ENERGY^Mitochondrial/Energy Metabolism Comment^0001|3|Supplementation Recommendations:   Cofactors needed to increase the breakdown of isocitrate to alpha-ketoglutarate are: Vit B3, (NAD), Mg, Mn.||||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|246|FT|MITOCHONDRIAL_ENERGY^Mitochondrial/Energy Metabolism Comment^0001|4|Suggested Treatment Considerations: Consider correlation with lipid profile and markers of metabolic and inflammatory status. Review dietary and metabolic factors influencing cholesterol synthesis where clinically indicated. Further evaluation may be warranted in cases of persistent or significant elevation. Management should be guided by the overall clinical context and associated laboratory findings.||||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|247|FT|MITOCHONDRIAL_ENERGY^Mitochondrial/Energy Metabolism Comment^0001|5|3-METHYLGLUTACONIC ACID ELEVATED: 3-Methylglutaconic acid (3-MGC) is a dicarboxylic acid intermediate in the leucine catabolism pathway. Under normal conditions, 3-methylglutaconyl-CoA is hydrated by the enzyme 3-methylglutaconyl-CoA hydratase to form HMG-CoA, which enters ketogenesis. When this step is impaired — due to genetic enzyme deficiency or acquired mitochondrial dysfunction — 3-MGC accumulates and is excreted in urine. Beyond leucine metabolism, 3-MGC has been established as a broader non-specific marker of mitochondrial inner membrane dysfunction, elevated across a range of mitochondrial disorders including Barth syndrome (TAZ gene mutation), DNAJC19-related cardiomyopathy, and SERAC1-related MEGDEL syndrome. In the functional medicine context, mild to moderate elevation most commonly reflects acquired mitochondrial stress and nutritional cofactor insufficiency (CoQ10, B2, carnitine, magnesium) rather than primary genetic deficiency.||||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|248|FT|MITOCHONDRIAL_ENERGY^Mitochondrial/Energy Metabolism Comment^0001|6|Clinical Significance: Elevated urinary 3-MGC is a meaningful indicator of mitochondrial dysfunction and warrants assessment of the broader mitochondrial marker pattern. Isolated mild elevation in a clinically well adult most likely reflects functional mitochondrial stress, cofactor depletion, or elevated oxidative burden rather than a primary genetic disorder. Elevation is most significant when found alongside globally reduced TCA cycle intermediates (low citric acid, isocitric acid, 2-oxoglutaric acid), indicating reduced mitochondrial throughput rather than an isolated enzyme defect. Clinically, elevation is associated with chronic fatigue and post-exertional malaise, exercise intolerance, reduced stamina, cognitive impairment, and in more severe presentations — cardiomyopathy and skeletal myopathy. Barth syndrome should be considered in males with elevated 3-MGC and cardiomyopathy. Marked elevation (greater than 10× the upper reference limit) accompanied by neurological symptoms, cardiomyopathy, myopathy, or significant neurodevelopmental concerns warrants referral for metabolic genetics evaluation to exclude primary mitochondrial disease.||||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|249|FT|MITOCHONDRIAL_ENERGY^Mitochondrial/Energy Metabolism Comment^0001|7|Clinically, symptoms are non-specific.||||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|250|FT|MITOCHONDRIAL_ENERGY^Mitochondrial/Energy Metabolism Comment^0001|8|From an organic acid pattern perspective, interpretation alongside alpha-ketoglutaric acid assists in determining whether downstream enzymatic congestion is present.||||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|251|FT|MITOCHONDRIAL_ENERGY^Mitochondrial/Energy Metabolism Comment^0001|9|From a functional medicine perspective, this finding should be interpreted as part of an overall mitochondrial pattern.||||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|252|FT|MITOCHONDRIAL_ENERGY^Mitochondrial/Energy Metabolism Comment^0001|10|A high level is suggestive of inhibition to the enzyme by Aluminum.||||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|253|FT|MITOCHONDRIAL_ENERGY^Mitochondrial/Energy Metabolism Comment^0001|11|2-OXOGLUTARIC ACID ELEVATED (URINE)||||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|254|FT|MITOCHONDRIAL_ENERGY^Mitochondrial/Energy Metabolism Comment^0001|12|Elevated urinary alpha-ketoglutaric acid suggests a bottleneck within the TCA cycle and altered nitrogen handling.||||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|255|FT|MITOCHONDRIAL_ENERGY^Mitochondrial/Energy Metabolism Comment^0001|13|Clinically, elevated alpha-ketoglutaric acid may be associated with fatigue, cognitive symptoms, or reduced exercise tolerance.||||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|256|FT|MITOCHONDRIAL_ENERGY^Mitochondrial/Energy Metabolism Comment^0001|14|From an organic acid pattern perspective, elevation often occurs alongside elevated succinic acid, reflecting downstream congestion and potential oxidative stress.||||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|257|FT|MITOCHONDRIAL_ENERGY^Mitochondrial/Energy Metabolism Comment^0001|15|From a functional medicine perspective, this finding should be interpreted in the context of mitochondrial efficiency, redox balance, and amino-acid metabolism.||||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|258|FT|MITOCHONDRIAL_ENERGY^Mitochondrial/Energy Metabolism Comment^0001|16|Elevations can be seen with nutrient cofactor deficiencies needed for the enzymatic conversion of α ketoglutarate such as vitamin B3, zinc, magnesium, manganese.||||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|259|FT|MITOCHONDRIAL_ENERGY^Mitochondrial/Energy Metabolism Comment^0001|17|Elevated urinary mevalonolactone may reflect increased activity of the mevalonate pathway, potentially indicating upregulated cholesterol and isoprenoid synthesis. This pattern may be observed in the context of metabolic dysregulation, increased anabolic demand, or altered lipid metabolism. In some cases, elevations may also be associated with inflammatory states, as the mevalonate pathway is involved in the production of intermediates important for immune cell function.||||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|260|FT|MITOCHONDRIAL_ENERGY^Mitochondrial/Energy Metabolism Comment^0001|18|While increased levels may provide insight into pathway activity, this finding is non-specific and should be interpreted in conjunction with lipid markers, inflammatory indicators, and overall metabolic context.||||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|261|FT|FATTY_ACID_OXIDATION^Fatty Acid Oxidation & Ketone Metabolism^0001|1|ADIPIC ACID ELEVATED (URINE): Adipic acid is a dicarboxylic fatty acid that increases when mitochondrial beta-oxidation is inefficient, often reflecting impaired fatty acid utilisation or carnitine insufficiency.||||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|262|FT|FATTY_ACID_OXIDATION^Fatty Acid Oxidation & Ketone Metabolism^0001|2|Clinically, elevations may be associated with fatigue, reduced exercise tolerance, muscle weakness, brain fog, or difficulty regulating weight. Interpretation should consider dietary intake, medications, and the broader metabolic context.||||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|263|FT|FATTY_ACID_OXIDATION^Fatty Acid Oxidation & Ketone Metabolism^0001|3|From a functional medicine perspective, management focuses on supporting mitochondrial beta-oxidation with carnitine, riboflavin (B2), niacin (B3), magnesium, CoQ10, optimising glycaemic control, and reducing excess dietary fat load, addressing underlying contributors rather than isolated suppression of the marker.||||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|264|FT|B_VITAMINS_AMINO_ACI^B-Vitamins/Amino Acids Comment^0001|1|GUANIDINOACETIC ACID ELEVATED: Guanidinoacetic acid (GAA) is an intermediate in creatine biosynthesis, formed from arginine and glycine via arginine:glycine amidinotransferase (AGAT) and subsequently converted to creatine by guanidinoacetate methyltransferase (GAMT) using S-adenosylmethionine (SAM) as a methyl donor.||||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|265|FT|B_VITAMINS_AMINO_ACI^B-Vitamins/Amino Acids Comment^0001|2|2-OXOISOCAPROIC ACID ELEVATED (URINE): Elevated urinary alpha-ketoisocaproic acid suggests impaired leucine catabolism and mitochondrial inefficiency.||||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|266|FT|B_VITAMINS_AMINO_ACI^B-Vitamins/Amino Acids Comment^0001|3|XANTHURENIC ACID ELEVATED (URINE): Elevated urinary xanthurenic acid suggests altered tryptophan metabolism, most commonly reflecting reduced vitamin B6-dependent enzymatic activity.||||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|267|FT|B_VITAMINS_AMINO_ACI^B-Vitamins/Amino Acids Comment^0001|4|2-OXO-4-METHYLTHIOBUTYRIC ACID ELEVATED: Description: 2-Oxo-4-methylthiobutyric acid (KMBA; also known as α-keto-γ-methiolbutyric acid) is the α-keto acid analogue of methionine, formed at the entry point of methionine catabolism via transamination. The reaction is catalysed by branched-chain aminotransferases, which transfer the amino group from methionine to an α-keto acid acceptor (typically α-ketoglutarate), producing KMBA. Under normal conditions, KMBA is further processed through the methionine salvage pathway to propionyl-CoA and methanethiol, ultimately entering the TCA cycle via succinyl-CoA. Elevated urinary KMBA reflects impaired downstream catabolism due to insufficient B6, B12, or folate cofactors; excess methionine substrate availability; reduced methylation capacity; or non-enzymatic generation from methionine via reactive oxygen species under conditions of elevated oxidative stress. KMBA therefore signals potential disruption at the critical junction between methionine metabolism, SAMe synthesis, transsulfuration, and glutathione production.||||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|268|FT|B_VITAMINS_AMINO_ACI^B-Vitamins/Amino Acids Comment^0001|5|Clinical Significance: Elevated KMBA indicates impaired methionine catabolism and/or transsulfuration pathway dysfunction with downstream consequences for methylation and glutathione synthesis. Reduced SAMe production impairs methylation reactions essential for neurotransmitter synthesis (dopamine, serotonin, norepinephrine), DNA and histone methylation, phospholipid metabolism, and immune regulation. Impaired transsulfuration reduces cysteine availability and consequently limits glutathione production  compromising phase II detoxification, antioxidant defence, and the body's capacity to manage chemical and oxidative burden. If remethylation is concurrently impaired, homocysteine may accumulate, representing an independent cardiovascular and neurological risk factor. Clinically, this pattern is associated with fatigue, cognitive impairment and brain fog, poor detoxification, chemical sensitivity, mood dysregulation, and susceptibility to inflammatory and autoimmune conditions. The combination of elevated KMBA, elevated xanthurenic acid, and low pyroglutamic acid is a strong functional indicator of B6 insufficiency as the primary driver. Plasma homocysteine and serum B12, folate, and B6 levels should be assessed to directly characterise methylation pathway status.||||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|269|FT|B_VITAMINS_AMINO_ACI^B-Vitamins/Amino Acids Comment^0001|6|N-ACETYLPHENYLALANINE ELEVATED: N-acetylphenylalanine is an acetylated derivative of the amino acid phenylalanine, formed through N-acetylation pathways as part of amino acid metabolism and phase II detoxification processes. It represents a minor urinary metabolite reflecting aromatic amino acid metabolism and conjugation activity.||||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|270|FT|B_VITAMINS_AMINO_ACI^B-Vitamins/Amino Acids Comment^0001|7|Suggested Treatment Considerations: Consider correlation with other markers of aromatic amino acid metabolism and gastrointestinal function. Review dietary protein intake and assess for factors influencing microbial metabolism where clinically indicated. Further evaluation should be guided by the overall clinical context and associated laboratory findings rather than the isolated marker elevation.||||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|271|FT|B_VITAMINS_AMINO_ACI^B-Vitamins/Amino Acids Comment^0001|8|Suggested Treatment Considerations: Consider evaluation of creatine metabolism and methylation capacity, including assessment of relevant nutrients such as folate and vitamin B12 where clinically indicated. Review dietary intake and consider factors influencing methylation demand. In cases of significant elevation or clinical suspicion, further investigation for inborn errors of metabolism may be warranted. Management should be guided by the overall clinical context and associated laboratory findings.||||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|272|FT|B_VITAMINS_AMINO_ACI^B-Vitamins/Amino Acids Comment^0001|9|Clinically, this may be associated with fatigue, muscle weakness, and reduced exercise tolerance.||||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|273|FT|B_VITAMINS_AMINO_ACI^B-Vitamins/Amino Acids Comment^0001|10|From an organic acid pattern perspective, elevation commonly occurs with 3-methylglutaric acid and other BCAA ketoacids, reflecting congestion within BCAA metabolic pathways.||||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|274|FT|B_VITAMINS_AMINO_ACI^B-Vitamins/Amino Acids Comment^0001|11|From a functional medicine perspective, this finding should be interpreted in the context of overall mitochondrial function and nutrient sufficiency rather than as an isolated abnormality.||||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|275|FT|B_VITAMINS_AMINO_ACI^B-Vitamins/Amino Acids Comment^0001|12|Consider supplementation with B1, B2, B3, B5, and lipoate to support enzyme function.||||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|276|FT|B_VITAMINS_AMINO_ACI^B-Vitamins/Amino Acids Comment^0001|13|Clinically, elevated xanthurenic acid may be associated with fatigue, mood disturbance, and impaired stress tolerance.||||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|277|FT|B_VITAMINS_AMINO_ACI^B-Vitamins/Amino Acids Comment^0001|14|From an organic acid pattern perspective, elevations often occur alongside kynurenic and quinolinic acid, indicating inflammatory diversion of tryptophan metabolism.||||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|278|FT|B_VITAMINS_AMINO_ACI^B-Vitamins/Amino Acids Comment^0001|15|From a functional medicine perspective, this finding should be interpreted in the context of vitamin B6 status and inflammatory burden.||||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|279|FT|B_VITAMINS_AMINO_ACI^B-Vitamins/Amino Acids Comment^0001|16|Elevated urinary N-acetylphenylalanine may reflect increased flux through phenylalanine metabolism and/or enhanced N-acetylation activity, which may occur in the context of increased substrate availability, altered amino acid metabolism, or metabolic demand. In addition, elevations may be influenced by gastrointestinal microbial metabolism of aromatic compounds, contributing to altered phenylalanine handling.||||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|280|FT|B_VITAMINS_AMINO_ACI^B-Vitamins/Amino Acids Comment^0001|17|This marker is non-specific and is best interpreted alongside other metabolites within the phenylalanine/tyrosine pathway and markers of microbial activity to assess potential patterns of metabolic or gastrointestinal involvement.||||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|281|FT|B_VITAMINS_AMINO_ACI^B-Vitamins/Amino Acids Comment^0001|18|Elevated urinary GAA may indicate impaired conversion of guanidinoacetate to creatine, which can occur in the context of guanidinoacetate methyltransferase (GAMT) deficiency, a rare inherited metabolic disorder. More commonly, elevated levels may reflect relative inefficiency in methylation-dependent conversion, increased endogenous synthesis, or altered creatine metabolism.||||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|282|FT|B_VITAMINS_AMINO_ACI^B-Vitamins/Amino Acids Comment^0001|19|From a biochemical perspective, accumulation of GAA may be associated with increased demand on methylation pathways, as the conversion of GAA to creatine represents a significant consumer of methyl groups. As such, elevations may also be observed in the context of impaired one-carbon metabolism or reduced methyl donor availability.||||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|283|FT|B_VITAMINS_AMINO_ACI^B-Vitamins/Amino Acids Comment^0001|20|This marker should be interpreted cautiously and in conjunction with other indicators of creatine metabolism and methylation status.||||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|284|FT|NEUROTRANSMITTER_MET^Neurotransmitter Metabolism Comment^0001|1|KYNURENIC ACID ELEVATED (URINE): Kynurenic acid reflects diversion of tryptophan metabolism down the kynurenine pathway, often driven by inflammation or immune activation.||||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|285|FT|NEUROTRANSMITTER_MET^Neurotransmitter Metabolism Comment^0001|2|Consider: Supplementation with Vitamin B6.||||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|286|FT|NEUROTRANSMITTER_MET^Neurotransmitter Metabolism Comment^0001|3|QUINOLINIC ACID ELEVATED (URINE): Quinolinic acid is a neuroactive metabolite within the kynurenine pathway. Elevation suggests inflammatory activation and excitotoxic stress.||||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|287|FT|NEUROTRANSMITTER_MET^Neurotransmitter Metabolism Comment^0001|4|Consider: Elimination of high tryptophan foods; supplementation with melatonin, B6, turmeric, garlic.||||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|288|FT|NEUROTRANSMITTER_MET^Neurotransmitter Metabolism Comment^0001|5|QUINOLINIC ACID/5-HIAA RATIO ELEVATED: Description: An elevated quinolinic acid/5-HIAA ratio reflects disproportionate tryptophan shunting through the excitotoxic kynurenine-quinolinic acid pathway at the expense of serotonin synthesis, indicating neuroinflammatory-driven tryptophan catabolism.||||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|289|FT|NEUROTRANSMITTER_MET^Neurotransmitter Metabolism Comment^0001|6|Clinical Significance: Elevated ratio is a significant indicator of neuroinflammation, IDO (indoleamine 2,3-dioxygenase) enzyme upregulation, and serotonin depletion with concomitant excitotoxic stress. Associated with treatment-resistant depression, suicidal ideation, chronic fatigue, cognitive impairment, and neurodegenerative conditions. IDO is activated by pro-inflammatory cytokines (IFN-γ, TNF-α, IL-6).||||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|290|FT|NEUROTRANSMITTER_MET^Neurotransmitter Metabolism Comment^0001|7|Suggested Treatment: Identify and address inflammatory triggers (gut dysbiosis, chronic infections, autoimmunity, dietary). Anti-inflammatory interventions: omega-3 fatty acids, curcumin, resveratrol. Support serotonin synthesis: L-tryptophan, 5-HTP, B6, zinc, SAMe. Consider IDO-modulating strategies. Neurological and psychiatric review if symptoms are severe.||||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|291|FT|NEUROTRANSMITTER_MET^Neurotransmitter Metabolism Comment^0001|8|Clinically, elevations may be associated with fatigue, mood changes, cognitive dysfunction, or pain syndromes. Interpretation should consider dietary intake, medications, and the broader metabolic context.||||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|292|FT|NEUROTRANSMITTER_MET^Neurotransmitter Metabolism Comment^0001|9|From a functional medicine perspective, management focuses on addressing inflammatory drivers, optimising vitamin B6 status, and supporting immune balance, addressing underlying contributors rather than isolated suppression of the marker.||||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|293|FT|NEUROTRANSMITTER_MET^Neurotransmitter Metabolism Comment^0001|10|Clinically, elevations may be associated with anxiety, depression, cognitive changes, and pain sensitivity. Interpretation should consider dietary intake, medications, and the broader metabolic context.||||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|294|FT|NEUROTRANSMITTER_MET^Neurotransmitter Metabolism Comment^0001|11|From a functional medicine perspective, management focuses on reducing neuroinflammation, supporting antioxidant defences, and optimising B-vitamin status, addressing underlying contributors rather than isolated suppression of the marker.||||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|295|FT|DETOXIFICATION_OXIDA^Detoxification / Oxidative Damage Comment:^0001|1|8-HYDROXY-2-DEOXYGUANOSINE ELEVATED (URINE): 8-OHdG is a marker of oxidative DNA damage. Elevation reflects increased oxidative stress and impaired antioxidant defence.||||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|296|FT|DETOXIFICATION_OXIDA^Detoxification / Oxidative Damage Comment:^0001|2|Consider: Supplementation with antioxidants such as vitamin C, E, N-acetyl cysteine, lipoate.||||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|297|FT|DETOXIFICATION_OXIDA^Detoxification / Oxidative Damage Comment:^0001|3|LEUKOTRIENE E4 ELEVATED: Leukotriene E4 (LTE4) is a stable urinary metabolite of the cysteinyl leukotrienes (LTC4, LTD4, and LTE4), which are lipid mediators derived from arachidonic acid via the 5-lipoxygenase pathway. These mediators play a key role in inflammatory and immune responses, particularly in MCAS, bronchoconstriction, vascular permeability, and recruitment of inflammatory cells.||||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|298|FT|DETOXIFICATION_OXIDA^Detoxification / Oxidative Damage Comment:^0001|4|Suggested Treatment Considerations: Consider correlation with clinical features of inflammatory or allergic disease, including respiratory symptoms or hypersensitivity patterns. Evaluation of factors contributing to inflammatory activation, including environmental exposures and immune triggers, may be appropriate. Management should be directed toward the underlying inflammatory process, with further investigation guided by the overall clinical context and associated laboratory findings.||||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|299|FT|DETOXIFICATION_OXIDA^Detoxification / Oxidative Damage Comment:^0001|5|Clinically, elevations may be associated with fatigue, accelerated ageing features, inflammatory symptoms. Interpretation should consider dietary intake, medications, and the broader metabolic context.||||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|300|FT|DETOXIFICATION_OXIDA^Detoxification / Oxidative Damage Comment:^0001|6|From a functional medicine perspective, management focuses on reducing oxidative load, enhancing antioxidant capacity, and addressing environmental or metabolic stressors, addressing underlying contributors rather than isolated suppression of the marker.||||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|301|FT|DETOXIFICATION_OXIDA^Detoxification / Oxidative Damage Comment:^0001|7|Elevated urinary LTE4 reflects increased systemic leukotriene production and is considered a non-invasive marker of inflammatory pathway activation, particularly within allergic and respiratory conditions. Increased levels may be observed in association with asthma, allergic disease, mast cell activation, and other inflammatory states, reflecting upregulation of leukotriene-mediated signalling.||||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|302|FT|DETOXIFICATION_OXIDA^Detoxification / Oxidative Damage Comment:^0001|8|As LTE4 represents a downstream metabolite, it provides an indication of overall leukotriene pathway activity rather than a specific site of inflammation, and should be interpreted in conjunction with clinical findings and other markers of inflammatory or immune activity.||||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|303|FT|ENVIRONMENTAL_XENOBI^Environmental/Xenobiotic Exposure Comment:^0001|1|ENVIRONMENTAL POLLUTANTS PROFILE: The reported markers in the Environmental Pollutants Profile commonly originate from industrial/manufacturing products or their associated byproducts. Exposures are often occupationally-related and typically through either inhalation or topical exposure.||||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|304|FT|ENVIRONMENTAL_XENOBI^Environmental/Xenobiotic Exposure Comment:^0001|2|3-METHYLHIPPURIC ACID ELEVATED (URINE): Elevated urinary 3-methylhippuric acid suggests increased exposure to xylene, as this metabolite represents glycine conjugation of xylene-derived methylbenzoic acids. Urinary methylhippuric acids are well-established biomarkers of xylene exposure.||||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|305|FT|ENVIRONMENTAL_XENOBI^Environmental/Xenobiotic Exposure Comment:^0001|3|Treatment:  Treatment options include limiting exposure to xylenes and  supportive supplements such as glycine and N-acetyl cysteine can support natural detoxification.||||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|306|FT|ENVIRONMENTAL_XENOBI^Environmental/Xenobiotic Exposure Comment:^0001|4|BENZOIC ACID ELEVATED (URINE): Elevated urinary benzoic acid suggests increased exposure to benzoate-containing foods, preservatives, or altered gut microbial metabolism. Benzoic acid is detoxified primarily through glycine conjugation to form hippuric acid.||||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|307|FT|ENVIRONMENTAL_XENOBI^Environmental/Xenobiotic Exposure Comment:^0001|5|Treatment:  Limiting exposure to toluene. Supportive supplements such as glycine and N-acetyl cysteine can support natural detoxification.||||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|308|FT|ENVIRONMENTAL_XENOBI^Environmental/Xenobiotic Exposure Comment:^0001|6|t,t-MUCONIC ACID ELEVATED (URINE): Elevated urinary t,t-muconic acid suggests increased exposure to benzene, as this metabolite represents a recognised biomarker of benzene metabolism and detoxification.||||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|309|FT|ENVIRONMENTAL_XENOBI^Environmental/Xenobiotic Exposure Comment:^0001|7|Treatment:  Treatment usually involves removing/limiting exposure; and therefore avoiding chronic exposure which can lead to severe consequences.||||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|310|FT|ENVIRONMENTAL_XENOBI^Environmental/Xenobiotic Exposure Comment:^0001|8|QUINOLINIC ACID ELEVATED (URINE): Elevated urinary quinolinic acid suggests increased flux through the kynurenine pathway of tryptophan metabolism, often associated with immune activation or inflammatory signalling. Quinolinic acid is a neuroactive metabolite with excitatory properties.||||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|311|FT|ENVIRONMENTAL_XENOBI^Environmental/Xenobiotic Exposure Comment:^0001|9|Treatment:  Treatments for high quinolinic acid focus on reducing its production and counteracting its neurotoxic effects, including dietary changes like increasing vitamin B6 and consuming antioxidants (e.g., sulforaphane, green tea polyphenols, curcumin), and supplements (melatonin, selenium, theanine).||||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|312|FT|ENVIRONMENTAL_XENOBI^Environmental/Xenobiotic Exposure Comment:^0001|10|4-HYDROXYBENZOIC ACID ELEVATED (URINE): Elevated urinary 4-hydroxybenzoic acid suggests increased exposure to parabens or altered metabolism of aromatic compounds. Parabens are commonly used as preservatives in cosmetics, personal care products, and some pharmaceuticals.||||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|313|FT|ENVIRONMENTAL_XENOBI^Environmental/Xenobiotic Exposure Comment:^0001|11|Treatment:  Treatments focus on improving gut health through dietary changes like increasing plant-based foods, fermented foods, and prebiotics while reducing artificial sweeteners and potentially eliminating paraben-containing products.||||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|314|FT|ENVIRONMENTAL_XENOBI^Environmental/Xenobiotic Exposure Comment:^0001|12|5-METHYLCYTOSINE ELEVATED: Urinary 5-methylcytosine (5-MC) is a modified nucleoside derived from DNA methylation and reflects global DNA methylation turnover and nucleic acid metabolism. Elevated levels may indicate increased DNA turnover, enhanced methylation flux, or increased degradation of methylated cytosine residues.||||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|315|FT|ENVIRONMENTAL_XENOBI^Environmental/Xenobiotic Exposure Comment:^0001|13|Suggested Treatment Considerations: Review potential contributors to increased oxidative stress and environmental exposures. Consider assessment of one-carbon metabolism and methyl donor status (e.g. folate, vitamin B12, choline) where clinically indicated. Supportive strategies may include optimisation of nutritional status and antioxidant capacity. Further evaluation should be guided by the overall clinical context and associated laboratory findings.||||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|316|FT|ENVIRONMENTAL_XENOBI^Environmental/Xenobiotic Exposure Comment:^0001|14|Metabolism of these products occurs via the liver detoxification pathways leading to excretion into the urine. Chronic exposures may also lead to build up of these products in fatty tissue deposits.||||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|317|FT|ENVIRONMENTAL_XENOBI^Environmental/Xenobiotic Exposure Comment:^0001|15|Clinically, elevated 3-methylhippuric acid may be associated with headaches, dizziness, fatigue, mucosal irritation, or central nervous system symptoms, depending on exposure magnitude and duration.||||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|318|FT|ENVIRONMENTAL_XENOBI^Environmental/Xenobiotic Exposure Comment:^0001|16|From an organic acid pattern perspective, elevated 3-methylhippuric acid may be observed alongside increased hippuric acid or other aromatic conjugates, reflecting increased aromatic solvent burden and glycine-dependent detoxification demand.||||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|319|FT|ENVIRONMENTAL_XENOBI^Environmental/Xenobiotic Exposure Comment:^0001|17|From a functional medicine perspective, this finding should be interpreted in the context of occupational, environmental, or household solvent exposure (e.g. paints, fuels, adhesives), alongside assessment of hepatic conjugation capacity and glycine availability, with emphasis on exposure identification and reduction.||||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|320|FT|ENVIRONMENTAL_XENOBI^Environmental/Xenobiotic Exposure Comment:^0001|18|Clinically, elevated benzoic acid may be associated with headaches, fatigue, gastrointestinal discomfort, or chemical sensitivity, although symptoms are often non-specific.||||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|321|FT|ENVIRONMENTAL_XENOBI^Environmental/Xenobiotic Exposure Comment:^0001|19|From an organic acid pattern perspective, elevated benzoic acid may be observed alongside elevated hippuric acid, indicating increased benzoate load or increased demand on glycine-dependent conjugation pathways.||||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|322|FT|ENVIRONMENTAL_XENOBI^Environmental/Xenobiotic Exposure Comment:^0001|20|From a functional medicine perspective, elevated benzoic acid should be interpreted in the context of dietary intake, glycine availability, gut microbial activity, and overall detoxification capacity rather than as an isolated finding.||||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|323|FT|ENVIRONMENTAL_XENOBI^Environmental/Xenobiotic Exposure Comment:^0001|21|Clinically, elevated t,t-muconic acid may be associated with fatigue, headaches, dizziness, or non-specific neurological symptoms, although clinical effects are highly dependent on exposure magnitude and duration.||||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|324|FT|ENVIRONMENTAL_XENOBI^Environmental/Xenobiotic Exposure Comment:^0001|22|From an organic acid pattern perspective, elevated t,t-muconic acid may be observed alongside other aromatic or solvent-related metabolites, reflecting increased aromatic hydrocarbon burden and hepatic detoxification demand.||||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|325|FT|ENVIRONMENTAL_XENOBI^Environmental/Xenobiotic Exposure Comment:^0001|23|From a functional medicine perspective, this finding should be interpreted in the context of environmental and occupational exposure sources (e.g. fuel vapours, tobacco smoke, solvents), indoor air quality, and overall detoxification capacity, with primary emphasis on exposure identification and reduction.||||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|326|FT|ENVIRONMENTAL_XENOBI^Environmental/Xenobiotic Exposure Comment:^0001|24|Clinically, elevated quinolinic acid may be associated with neurocognitive symptoms such as brain fog, mood disturbance, irritability, sleep disruption, or heightened pain sensitivity, although symptom expression varies.||||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|327|FT|ENVIRONMENTAL_XENOBI^Environmental/Xenobiotic Exposure Comment:^0001|25|From an organic acid pattern perspective, elevated quinolinic acid is often observed alongside alterations in other tryptophan metabolites, indicating inflammatory diversion of tryptophan metabolism away from serotonin and melatonin pathways.||||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|328|FT|ENVIRONMENTAL_XENOBI^Environmental/Xenobiotic Exposure Comment:^0001|26|From a functional medicine perspective, this finding should be interpreted in the context of immune activation, inflammatory burden, and overall balance of tryptophan metabolism rather than as a primary neurological disorder.||||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|329|FT|ENVIRONMENTAL_XENOBI^Environmental/Xenobiotic Exposure Comment:^0001|27|Clinically, elevated 4-hydroxybenzoic acid may be associated with non-specific symptoms such as fatigue, headaches, or endocrine-related concerns, although many individuals remain asymptomatic.||||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|330|FT|ENVIRONMENTAL_XENOBI^Environmental/Xenobiotic Exposure Comment:^0001|28|From an organic acid pattern perspective, elevated 4-hydroxybenzoic acid may be seen alongside other aromatic or phenolic metabolites, reflecting cumulative preservative or polyphenol exposure.||||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|331|FT|ENVIRONMENTAL_XENOBI^Environmental/Xenobiotic Exposure Comment:^0001|29|From a functional medicine perspective, this finding should be interpreted in the context of environmental and personal care exposures, hepatic conjugation capacity, and cumulative endocrine-disrupting burden, with emphasis on reducing ongoing exposure.||||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|332|FT|ENVIRONMENTAL_XENOBI^Environmental/Xenobiotic Exposure Comment:^0001|30|This pattern may be observed in the context of increased cellular turnover, oxidative stress, inflammatory processes, or enhanced DNA repair activity, and may also be influenced by environmental exposures, including certain xenobiotics.||||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|333|FT|ENVIRONMENTAL_XENOBI^Environmental/Xenobiotic Exposure Comment:^0001|31|While 5-MC provides insight into methylation turnover, it does not directly assess methylation capacity. Interpretation should be made in conjunction with clinical findings and, where appropriate, other markers of one-carbon metabolism and oxidative stress.||||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpathOBX|334|FT|METHODOLOGY^Methodology^0001|1|Liquid Chromatography-Mass Spectrometry (LC-MS/MS/MS), Gas Chromatography-MS (GC/MS), Automated Chemistry/Immunochemistry||||||F|||20260513072228+1000|0001^NutriPATH^nutrpath